article.description: The Connecticut home crowd rarely leaves disappointed.
article.headline: Huskies tie NCAA record with 69  home wins
article.linkText: UConn tops NC State, ties mark for home wins
article.story:
HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The Connecticut home crowd rarely leaves
disappointed.

On Monday, top-ranked UConn sent the sellout crowd of 16,294
fans at the Hartford Civic Center home happy once again with an
87-53 win over North Carolina State to tie an NCAA mark of 69
straight home wins.

"Our fans are great. They show up every night, rain or shine or
snow. It doesn't matter who we play," UConn coach Geno Auriemma
said. "Our fans come out every night."

Ann Strother led the way with a career-high 20 points, including
five 3-pointers, another personal best. She scored the first eight
points of the game, which included a pair of 3s.

"I think we passed the ball really well," Strother said.
"Against the zone we got the ball moving pretty quick. It's just
an overall reflection of our ball movement."

All-American Diana Taurasi added 18 and had eight assists.

The Huskies (9-0) matched the NCAA record set seven years ago by
Tennessee. The Huskies snapped the Lady Vols' streak with 59-53 win
in Knoxville on Jan. 26, 1996. Tennessee handed UConn's its last
home loss, 72-71 on Feb. 2, 2000.

Since then the Huskies have won three national titles and set an
NCAA women's mark with 70-game winning streak that ended last
season. UConn will have a chance to get its 70th straight home win
when it hosts No. 4 Duke on Saturday.

The win also marked the 102nd straight home sellout for UConn.

"I think in women's basketball we have a unique situation that
no one else has and our fans are a big part of it. They've been a
big part of it for the last 10 years," Auriemma said.

Kaayla Chones had 15 points for the Wolfpack (7-5), held to
34-percent shooting and outscored 44-24 in the paint.

UConn put the game away early, hitting 12 of its first 14 shots
in the first nine minutes for 27-9 lead. Taurasi was nearly
flawless in that stretch. She made her first four shots and had
four assists.

She played sparingly the rest of the half after picking up her
second foul.

"When we get on the court we want to dominate," Taurasi said.
"Every time we touched the ball we were looking to get in the
lane. We had more dribble penetration tonight than we've had all
season."

The Huskies took away the Wolfpack's inside game by getting
leading scorer Chones into foul trouble quickly. Chones, who leads
the ACC in double-doubles with 24, picked up her third foul with
4:34 left and sat out the rest of the half.

UConn led 47-24 at the break, but with Chones back in the second
half the Wolfpack quickly went on the offensive. She had five
points in a 7-0 run early in the half. The Huskies countered with a
10-0 run, fueled by two 3-pointers from Strother.

Kendra Bell added 11 for the Wolfpack.

The sellout crowd also gave a rousing ovation during
introductions to N.C. State's Hall-of-Fame coach Kay Yow, now in
her 29th season with the Wolfpack.

"It's a great atmosphere," Yow said. "It just doesn't exist
all over the country. It's a great sixth person for the team. Not
that they need a sixth person."
